column1: Data Supplied By: National Livestock Reporting Service
Data source: National Livestock Reporting Service
Please see terms of use here: https://www.mla.com.au/general/Terms-and-conditions/data-and-information/

Numbers jumped up and the quality remains good with plenty of cattle in forward condition. Yearlings were well supplied with good numbers of medium and heavy weights offered. Lighter weaners and yearlings under 300kg were limited. Feeders were the strength but they pulled back on steers over 480kg. Grown steers and heifers were well supplied with plenty in the 500 to 600kg weight range and there was a good run of heavy cows. The market held firm on most of the light and medium weight yearlings, trade cattle were steady while extra heavy feeders eased. Grown steers and heifers sold from a firm to easier trend as did the cows.
 
Best of the butcher vealers reached 330c and weaner steers sold to 380c/kg. Medium weight feeders mainly sold from 265c to 378c/kg. lighter weights to back ground reached 406c/kg. Heavy feeders sold from 329c to 368c/kg and the extra heavy weights over 480c were 10c softer with most 300c to 350c/kg. Feeder heifers were also firm on average selling from 257c to 321c/kg, heavy weights in forward condition reached 318c/kg. trade heifers were firm although a higher top price was achieved, most selling from 280c to 324c/kg. Steers ranged from 328c to 350c/kg.
 
Grown steers and bullocks were firm to 5c softer selling from 296c to 364c and heifers followed a similar trend selling from 290c to 350c/kg. Cows were firm to 4c softer with the heavy weights 260c to 292c and the medium weight 2 score lifted 3c, 220c to 256c/kg.
